        <div class="user-comment">
             
             
                          
              
             <p class="comment">Unfortunately, Connecticut will continue to build highways and use eminent domain to widen existing roads. It's really backwards to ignore the benefits of mass transit linking central Connecticut to parts south and north. Central Connecticut is increasingly growing older and poorer as college graduates and those seeking opportunity leave the Hartford and New Haven area for Boston or New York City. If rail was an easy and inexpensive commuting option it would at least help to curb the brain drain from Connecticut. I have lived for eighteen years in New York City after graduating from UCONN and now meet recent UCONN graduates who have moved to the city. Staying put is not an option and commuting right now is not convenient from parts north of New Haven. Connecticut had the opportunity to receive a greater share of rail funding in order to modernize the current rails and apparently had a poor plan. Friends of mine from England tell me about high speed trains that leave London and arrive on time hundreds of miles outside the city in record time. So much for the United States becoming a Third World country as we continue to fall behind in mass transit and clean energy.</p>
             <p class="user date">ConcernedCitizen35 (01/31/2010, 8:30 PM )</p>
             
